 combat has been vastly improved; in Human Revolution the normal pistol was an unchallenged king out of the other weapons, but in Mankind Divided each weapon has their own merit (Some large open fields for the sniper rifle, different types of special ammunition, effective range and piercing, etc). Gunfights have more glasscannon than bullet sponge enemies, which is something I enjoy as well. Adam's health felt quite low, but I haven't tried out the Titan shields yet, which should give Adam Jensen a much higher survivability. Some situations felt poorly planned, some ambushed start you in a 3v1 situation without cover, making it hard to find cover or take them out fast enough on the highest difficulties.\nThe stealth system was improved as well with multiple phases like panic, hostile and searching. Although this was already present in the predecessor, it's more fleshed out in Mankind Divided by making the stages of NPC's known from the start. The ability to pull enemies with you behind cover in hand to hand combat also was a quality of life improvement, making the game react more to your intentions (Because you almost always want to hide bodies).\nThe amount of possible paths to locations was even bigger than in Human Revolution, making every playstyle viable instead of a choice between vents and following the main path; almost every floor was a new maze of possibilities.\nThe cityhub felt a little less diverse than Human Revolution which had a wider variety of scenery with Hengsha and Detroit, as Mankind Divided only has Prague and a small moment in Golem City. It was, however, much more impressive than it's predecessor as the area's changed much more because of new events. Shops are all over the city, which made selling items and buying new ones quite easy. Shop interaction was kind of flawed; you have to sit through 4 one-liners of the NPC which narrow down to \"I sell items. Please buy items?\" before you get access to their computer (which contains their wares), and exiting wants you to confirm your exiting multiple times.\nThere is only one bossfight in Mankind Divided compared to Human Revolution's multiple, but it doesn't feel like this game is lacking them. \n\nTL;DR:\n[list]\n    [*]Atmosphere feels rich and is vastly visible.\n    [*]Combat and stealth is improved and feels great with multiple options.\n    [*]Storyline is good, albeit the earlygame connection is weak.\n    [*]Possible paths have increased tremendously, making even more playstyles viable.\n[/list]\nIt's a great game, a worthy successor of the earlier Deus Ex franchise.", "received_for_free": false, "timestamp_created": 1505596128, "written_during_early_access": false, "timestamp_updated": 1505596128, "recommendationid": "35007283", "language": "english", "votes_down": 2, "steam_purchase": true, "weighted_vote_score": "0.539086", "voted_up": true}, {"author": {"last_played": 1504873281, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 0, "num_reviews": 3, "playtime_forever": 2395, "steamid": "76561197962569705", "num_games_owned": 303}, "votes_funny": 0, "votes_up": 11, "comment_count": 0, "review": "I refrained from playing DE:MD until September 2017 due to the critical reception by the community and critics.  I recently completed my first mostly-stealthy and fully pacifist playthrough over the course of five or so engaging nights of play and I wish I'd gotten to it sooner.  \n\nThis review concerns only the base experience, as I haven't gotten into any of the DLCs.  It also does not comment on the microtransaction model, which I understand has caused some uproar.\n\nIt may be the separation of years between playing HR and MD, but I think MD is equal to its predecessor in terms of story engagement.  I did all but one of the side quests and each one of them was well-written and impactful, with the possible exception of the one concerning the underground news ring.  Each step in the story felt like a big deal - I didn't feel like the game was wasting my time, and the world