ther hidden agenda. But, no.\nHe's just a soldier waging his own war to the world. All the steps between are standard blockbuster scenario.\nBut that's not the main point of MD.\n\nMD's main focus is the city itself, how it evolves, its inhabitants and how they cope with the events.\nIn that regard, MD is a success, boasting one of (if not the best) environnemental storytelling in videogame history.\n\nUnlike classic RPG, quests aren't given to you.\nYou have to look for them. Around a street corner, inside an apartment, behind a garbage bin.\nSure, there is an info dealer who can direct you to points of interest. Yes, some side-quests show themselves to you. Yet, most of them appear naturally, while exploring, or just passing by.\nThe glitch and the copycat are the two side-quests which represents how questing should be handled from now on: surprise, mystery, danger, trap, emotional stake.\n\nUnlike RPG, lore isn't force-feeded to you.\nYou have to look around, read mails in an ordinary computer, move through tossed beers, broken utilities, burned painting or manicles on the walls (cf look closely in the Dvalis Theater), to understand the inhabitants' personnal stories.\nNothing complies you to do so. But it's still here, waiting.\nThe story of the mom who died in the rumbles of the station, the hope of young artists trying to get out, the despair of a father who has lost his daughter to Dvalis lies.\n\nSome complains about the game are the characters. Too one-sided, quite boring, nothing enthralling.\nIndeed, some of them are.\nThe \"rival\" is so-so. The big bad is \"monolithic\". The love interest is inexistant. Alex is more a plot device than anything else. The crazy aug specialist has potential, but is only used at two points in the game.\nI barely met (stun-guned is more precise) the Dvali boss, despite hearing about him all the game long.\nBut others shine.\nAdam's boss, who must both deal with global terrorist attacks, illuminati manipulations, a gay divorce and a daughter tortured to death by TWM to force him into augmenting her (and probably blackmailing him later with a killswitch).\nThe Rabiah's recrutor, whose sincerity and pragmatism are harshly treated by the police forces.\nSamizdat team. Of course.\nHobos and homelesses, pouring out some nice philosophies or social critiques if you take the time to listen to them.\nSmiley and Chang are funny to speak to. Chikane and weapon sellers ( \"Tars is the man!\" \"F***g Clanks!!\" ) too.\nThe female cop trying to do her job despite the general anti-aug policy. The shrink (aka Madam Photograph? ) and her shady behavior. Helle and the professionnal killer.\nSo, yeah, the writing isn't poor, it's different. The player has to play for it, to dig, to deduce, to speak to, to listen to, to look at every doors, windows, posters and props.\nIt's \"show, don't tell\" made into a videogame. The story is right here, it's up to you to unravel it.\n\nI admit, MD is less a surprise than HR.\nThere isn't much novelty. The game stats speak for themselves: barely half the players have used any of the new augments.\nThe breach mode, I did not play. I'm here for Deus Ex. And Deus Ex is solo.\nThere're strange choices in the first hours of the game.\nWhy the station bombing isn't playable? It should have been a great scene, forcing the player to explore and act in a crisis (save Alex or save random people? ).\nWhy letting so many threads unresolved at the end? Surely we could have got a few more bones to chew without compromising the release schedule.\nWhy the ending feels that rushed? Instead of a nice political, economic and societal \"what if\", we only watch a broadcast news reviewing the public impacts of our choices during the game.\n\nI got the game during a steamsale, for 20 bucks with Criminal Past (a really good DLC btw).\nAt that price tag, with all the content, story and overall presentation, I cannot think of a lesser appreciation than \"stellar\".\nThe only real bad point I 