rough (while triggering weapon customization at the tail end of an autosave - couldn't reproduce), but I ran into zero game-breaking or progress-halting issues. \n\nThere were some minor sound balance issues in some areas where environmental sounds or music made it difficult to hear NPC conversation, but nothing that made me put the game down or even tweak my settings. \n\nI did have to crank down anti-aliasing despite having a hexacore I7 chip backed by an nVidia 1070 GPU. Something about their implementation of MSAA feels off; I couldn't hold good performance while it was turned up. \n\n:: Story \n\nDE:MD picks up after the story of Deus Ex: Human Revolution, plus a couple of years wherein extra story elements were crammed. The game ramps up fairly quickly though the initial trips through Prague seem like they're dragging - then you realize Prague /is/ the main game setting, as it's where all the side missions happen, and they take up the bulk of your time. This is more of a hub-game, not a destination-game. \n\nUnfortunately this is where my big criticism is; DE:MD's story comes off as half-baked. By the midpoint of the game they've ramped up the scope of possible conspiracies to involve Everything and Everyone, then by the time the game finishes you realize it still involves Everything and Everyone That's Still Alive. None of the main plot points are resolved by the game's completion and there's a completely naked telegraph for a future sequel (which, due to poor sales, is unlikely to happen any time soon). \n\nThe \"Story DLCs\" that were released include one prequel mission and one \"this also happened\" mission without wrapping up any of the loose threads. The game won't bring you closure.\n\n:: Verdict\n\nDE:MD was worth playing if you enjoy stealth/action types of games. I wouldn't pay anything near full price; wait for sales or historic lows.", "received_for_free": false, "timestamp_created": 1506874472, "written_during_early_access": false, "timestamp_upd